A 23-year-old protester was allegedly shot dead by a motorist on Thursday (07 July) at Mgcobaneni trust outside KaBokweni, in Mpumalanga. The motorist also committed suicide later at his parental home at Chweni trust. It is alleged that the protester was amongst four people who were responsible for the road closures around the area. According to a source known to Daily Sun, the motorist who has been identified as Gideon Mavundla (38) attempted to remove the stones that the protesters were using to barricade the road. "The four men were standing by the road when the motorist produced his firearm and shot the protester three times on the upper body, the deceased died instantly," said the source The protester has since been identified as Dominic Nyundu. Since Wednesday, taxi drivers as well as community members, embarked on a fuel hike protest calling for the government to reconsider its decision after the latest increase in fuel prices. Some parts of the province remain closed and businesses have also been affected. At least two people have been killed since the protest started, two people were reported to be injured. Mpumalanga police spokesman, Brigadier Selvy Mohlala said 37 people have been arrested. He said one suspect has been arrested and charged with murder and an inquest has also been opened for the murder of the protester. He said different police units have been deployed to identify hotspots to deal with the ongoing protest. Mpumalanga Community Safety MEC, Vusi Shongwe has since condemned the actions of the protesters. He said: " Our country is still reeling from a ravaging pandemic that left many people without jobs. Therefore any person whose actions sabotage the economy must be harshly dealt with. "Communities should refrain from blockading the road because that is not only dangerous for people requiring urgent medical attention, it also sabotages our economy, " says Shongwe